Check the commits: git log --oneline 72651ee~1..6cc0959
Read the full diff: git diff 72651ee~1..6cc0959
Read modified files in full for context.

Review in 4 phases:

Phase 0 — Contract Pack verification (highest priority):
- Read the Contract Pack section in the plan
- Verify each invariant has test coverage
- Verify each counter_example mitigation is implemented
- If Contract Pack is missing or incomplete -> record process finding, continue

Phase 1 — Test Adequacy:
- Are all declared boundary conditions tested?
- Are there only happy path tests?
- Would tests fail with wrong implementation?
- Identify weak assertions (assert x is not None, assert result, assert len(x) > 0) -> test-gap MED

Phase 2 — Behavioral Correctness:
A. Correctness: implementation matches intent, boundary inputs, exception paths
B. Boundary conditions: for each new/modified function, construct 3 input types: empty ([]/{}/None), single element, overflow/extreme
C. Integration: callers updated, imports complete, migration reversible, API compatible
D. Security: no hardcoded secrets, input validation, no injection vectors
E. Architecture quality: import direction correct (lower layer doesn't reference upper), no cross-module internal variable access, no new hardcoded constants, new files <300 lines with single responsibility
F. Root cause quality (bug fix): evidence supports root cause conclusion
G. Regression risk: does modification affect unplanned functionality? Are other callers of shared functions verified?

Phase 3 — Non-tested Risks:
- Untested side effects: state, concurrency, permissions, idempotency, timezone, null values
- Is implementation overfitting to pass tests?

Finding Classification (REQUIRED for every finding):
- code-bug: implementation defect
- test-gap: test coverage defect
- design-concern: design-level question
- suggestion: improvement suggestion

PASS/FAIL: code-bug or test-gap HIGH/MED unresolved -> FAIL.

For each finding use structured format: ID, Severity, Category, Evidence (file:line), Impact, Suggested action.
Conclude with PASS or FAIL.
Write in Chinese.
